<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="78284147-ebaf-549f-af29-cd9663c9d80b" activityNameId="98d3159f-5742-47aa-9e32-289791cff548" parentActivityId="ff737e6f-04e2-5be8-875a-360015350152" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">transport, pipeline, offshore, long distance, natural gas</activityName>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">This dataset describes the energy consumption and the emissions linked to the transport of natural gas from the place of production to export in an onshore pipeline.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">This dataset describes the energy consumption, emissions (including losses), and infrastructure requirements for the transport of 1 metric ton (based on a density of 0.735 kg/m3) natural gas over one kilometre in an onshore pipeline at the location specified by the activity’s geography. The construction, surveillance, and decommissioning of the network is considered in the separate activity for pipeline construction, which is an input to this transport activity. The energy requirements for the compression station are included over the input ‘natural gas, burned in gas turbine’. The distribution and delivery to customer via reduced pressure lines (1-5 bar overpressure for industries) and households (0.1 bar overpressure) is not considered here, but rather in the corresponding market activities for natural gas at high and low pressure, respectively.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset describes the transport of natural gas via long-distance offshore pipelines [metric ton*km], from Indonesia to the importing countries.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The transportation of natural gas via long-distance pipelines is driven by compressor stations fueled by natural gas. The share of liquefied natural gas (LNG) in inter-regional trade of natural gas has increased steadily over the past decades, and it equaled the volume exported in pipelines around 2019-2020. (BP 2022)</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">The emission data availble from IEA 2022 (used by Meili et al. 2023 for modelling the extraction of oil and gas) is only available on the level of natural gas producing countries and can neither be allocated to the different distribution stages (long-distance, regional, local) nor converted to tonne*km which is required for modelling the long-distance transport. Hence, Bussa et al. (2023) relied on other data sources.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Gas leakage and energy requirements are the two main factors differing between regions for pipeline transport (both offshore and onshore). According to Bussa et al. (2023, section 4.2.2) the leakage in RER and RNA is set to 0.019%, and 0.204% other regions of the world. Similarly, Bussa et al. estimated the energy requirements in RER and RNA to 0.9% versus 2.2% for the rest. Emissions and infrastructure need of the compressor stations are modelled with the input of “natural gas, burned in gas turbine” (i.e., for energy requirements).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">This is delivering the service of transportation of 1 metric ton across the distance of 1 km. This service only considers the transportation of fuels, like natural gas, through offshore long-distance pipeline. The pipeline operates with compressor stations fueled by natural gas. Gas leakages are taken into account.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Reference(s):</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Bussa, M., N. Jungbluth, Ch. Meili (2023) Life cycle inventories for long-distance transport and distribution of natural gas. ESU-services Ltd. Schaffhausen, Switzerland. Available from: http://esu-services.ch/data/public-lci-reports/</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="4bb326bb-e3df-4d71-b77c-f9a2f7e55536">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">4930:Transport via pipeline</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="14ba15f4-7d7e-11de-9ae2-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">ID</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Indonesia</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset refers only to the delivery of high pressure natural fas, which has a pressure of 70 bar. The delivery of teh gas is performed via offshore pipelines.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2021-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The data for emissions is from 2006, the data for energy requirements from 2001</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
