    <modellingAndValidation>
      <representativeness systemModelId="290c1f85-4cc4-4fa1-b0c8-2cb7f4276dce">
        <systemModelName xml:lang="en">Allocation, cut-off by classification</systemModelName>
        <samplingProcedure xml:lang="en">The pipeline transportation is driven by compressor stations, for which the energy requirements were derived for different regions from literature (Bussa et al., 2023, tab 4.6). Also the losses and generally leakages during long-distance transport are estimated based on various studies (Bussa et al., 2021, tab 4.8). The energy use data of the pipeline is based on qualified estimates from industrial experts for the years 2014 and 2015 (Müller-Syring et al. 2016; Schuller et al. 2017). The infrastructure needs are based on values given in Schori et al. 2012 (qualified estimates). Dutch company reports (Gasunie 1998; 2001) are used for the amount of condensate (verified data partly based on assumptions) and refrigerant emissions. The refrigerants used are updated to current legislation (non-expert estimate). Other emissions are calculated based on the loss rates (qualified estimates) and a generic natural gas composition. For the auxiliary datasets “Natural gas, burned in gas turbine”, the natural gas input is specified by country of origin. For the emissions, generic factors were used. Reference(s): Müller-Syring G., Große C., Glandien J. and Eyßer M. (2016) Critical Evaluation of Default Values for the GHG Emissions of the Natural Gas Supply Chain. DBI Gas- und Umwelttechnik GmbH. Schuller O., Reuter B., Hengstler J., Whitehouse S. and Zeitzen L. (2017) Greenhouse Gas Intensity of Natural Gas Transport. ThinkStep. Schori S. and Frischknecht R. (2012) Life Cycle Inventory of Natural Gas Supply. ESU Services Ltd. Uster, Switzerland. Report commissioned by Swiss Federal Office of Energy (SFOE) Gasunie (1998) Environmental annual report 1997. N.V. Nederlandse Gasunie, Groningen, retrieved from: www.gasunie.nl/eng/f_gm1.htm. Gasunie (2001) Safety, Health &amp; Environment - annual report 2000. N.V. Nederlandse Gasunie, Groningen, retrieved from: www.gasunie.nl.</samplingProcedure>
        <extrapolations xml:lang="en">The data for emissions are based on European data and for energy requirements on German data.</extrapolations>
      </representativeness>
      <review reviewedMajorRelease="3" reviewedMinorRelease="0" reviewedMajorRevision="0" reviewedMinorRevision="1" reviewerId="847a56f5-d9e5-4a65-ab51-b056e0039130" reviewerName="Avraam Symeonidis" reviewerEmail="Symeonidis@ecoinvent.org" reviewDate="2023-10-06">
        <otherDetails xml:lang="en"/>
